 "mechanism": "Ferrosomes are membrane-bound organelles containing iron, phosphorus, and oxygen that help C. difficile detoxify excess iron and adapt to sudden iron influx after iron deprivation.",
 "evidence": "Pi et al. showed that fezB-deficient cells exhibited a growth lag when iron-deprived cells were exposed to a strong dose of iron sulfate, suggesting the fez system protects against toxic iron influx."
 },
 {
 "mechanism": "The fez operon is induced by iron deprivation and by calprotectin (an iron-sequestering protein induced by inflammation), allowing C. difficile to counteract nutritional immunity.",
 "evidence": "Calprotectin upregulated the fez operon in vitro and in vivo; in mice lacking calprotectin, colonization and weight loss were unaffected by loss of the ferrosome system."
 },
 {
 "mechanism": "The fez operon (fezA and fezB) is necessary and sufficient for formation of ferrosome structures containing Fe, O, and P, associated with FezA and FezB proteins near the cell membrane.",
 "evidence": "Using microscopy and spectroscopy, the authors showed that the fez operon is required for ferrosome formation."
 },
 {
 "mechanism": "Loss of ferrosomes (fezB-deficient C. difficile) reduces bacterial burden, weight loss, and intestinal inflammation in murine models of CDI.",
 "evidence": "Mice infected with fezB-deficient C. difficile had decreased bacterial burden and less weight loss after4 days; in a colitis model, lower colonization and less intestinal inflammation were observed."
 },
 {
 "mechanism": "High colonic iron (e.g., from iron supplements) can increase abundance of Clostridioides species including C. difficile and C. perfringens, and may modify antibiotic efficacy.",
 "evidence": "Reference to controlled intervention studies in Kenyan children: iron supplements significantly increased abundances of Clostridioides, including C. difficile and C. perfringens."
 }
